This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it focuses on improving the performance of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) on image classification and object detection tasks. Additionally, the paper proposes a new pooling layer that enhances discriminative features during the downsampling procedure, which is a common technique used in CNNs for computer vision tasks. 

The paper also discusses the importance of proper pooling strategies for discriminative tasks, which suggests that it could belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

Furthermore, the paper proposes a new layer based on local importance modeling, which could fall under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

The paper also presents experimental results on different architectures and datasets, which could suggest that it belongs to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper focuses on improving the performance of CNNs on image classification and object detection tasks, which could suggest that it belongs to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
